full_text: Now I'm going to add the type criterion that I configured in the last demo to the user interface, specifically, the activity search page. The first thing to do is create a display key for the criterion. The label it displays should read activity type. Now I'll collapse this node. And take a look at the activity search page. As you can see, there are two main elements. The input set on the left is for required criteria. Remember that you must specify at least one criterion from this group. Also, Guidewire does not support adding a new required criterion. The input set on the right is for optional criteria. I will add my new criterion here. So I double click to navigate to that input set. In the tool box, I start searching for type key input. When type key input appears, I click it. I drop the new type key input immediately below priority. Immediately, some errors appear. I will configure the widget and the errors will be cleared. Users should, obviously, be able to pick a value to search on. So I set the value of the editable property to true. I'll give the widget an ID. And set its label to the display key I created. Finally, I'll set the value of the widget to the type of the activity. Setting the value automatically sets the value type. To test my work, I'll start the Claim Center server. When the server is started, I navigate to Claim Center. And log in as Andy Applegate. On the activity search screen, I'll search for activities assigned to my group, whose type is general. When I search, a number of activities are found. This concludes the Modifying Claim Center search screens demonstration.
